Personally I don't agree with the post, starting from his analysis, of the first snippet of code:<p><pre><code>  group->text = (char *) malloc(sizeof(char) * strlen(params->text));
  if (group->text == NULL) {
	res = MP_MEM;
  }
  strcpy(group->text, params->text);
</code></pre>
I don't think that the sizeof(char) or the casting of the pointer are of any danger and increase readability (we are not coding to show how well we know the standard).<p>The poster is right about the missing space in the malloc call for the NULL char, but I see a bigger threat calling a malloc with the size coming from a strlen: it can be really dangerous if somehow you miss a NULL terminator.<p>And again, same complain about the usage of <i>strcpy</i>. The standard gives us <i>strncpy</i> that put a limiting size in the copy operation.<p>_Personally I think that strcpy has to be avoided as a plague being a source of buffer overruns error as no other call in the C library._
